<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="da000ad8-1d72-52b9-94f4-0b41481e95f4" activityNameId="da666e23-2f82-42ab-87e7-2d4d265c9241" parentActivityId="2b208a45-ce52-4e6d-b736-9e29ce2a60a2" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">electrolyte production, for Li-ion battery</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when chemicals enter the process at the factory.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the production of liquid electrolyte for Li-ion batteries at factory gate.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg liquid electrolyte, used in Li-ion batteries. The electrolyte is made of a lithium salt dissolved in a liquid solution of organic solvents and additives.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">- Dai, Q., Kelly, J. C., Gaines, L., &amp; Wang, M. (2019). Life cycle analysis of lithium-ion batteries for automotive applications. Batteries, 5(2), 48. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">- Schmuch, R., Wagner, R., Hörpel, G., Placke, T., &amp; Winter, M. (2018). Performance and cost of materials for lithium-based rechargeable automotive batteries. Nature Energy, 3(4), 267-278. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Solvionic. (2019). Cleaner solvents for sustainable chemistry - Products Retrieved from https://en.solvionic.com/products/1m-lipf6-in-ec-dmc-1-1-vol.-with-2wt.-vc-99.9</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chagnes, A. (2015). Lithium battery technologies: electrolytes. In Lithium Process Chemistry (pp. 167-189): Elsevier.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">- </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Dai, Q., Kelly, J. C., Gaines, L., &amp; Wang, M. (2019). Life cycle analysis of lithium-ion batteries for automotive applica-tions. Batteries, 5(2), 48. </text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="97cb61b4-f165-4227-831a-0df604658946">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">20:Manufacture of chemicals and chemical products</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Geography not specified,</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Typically the electrolyte in Li-ion batteries is liquid, and made of a mixture of organic solvents such as ethylene carbonate (EC) and dimethyl carbonate (DMC), a lithium salt such as lithium hexafluoro phosphate (LiPF6) and a small amount of additive such as vinyl carbonate (VC) as follows: 1M LiPF6 in 1:1 EC:DMC + 2%wt VC. The use of two solvents with high permittivity, i.e. EC, and low viscosity, i.e. DMC, promote ionic dissociation and ion mobility at the same time. The additives are used to improve the performance of Li-ion batteries, for instance to protect the electrode surface from degradation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Chagnes, A. (2015). Lithium battery technologies: electrolytes. In Lithium Process Chemistry (pp. 167-189): Elsevier.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Dai, Q., Kelly, J. C., Gaines, L., &amp; Wang, M. (2019). Life cycle analysis of lithium-ion batteries for automotive applica-tions. Batteries, 5(2), 48. </text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2019-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period is from 2019 (year of the publication of data) and 2020 (year of the dataset)</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
